    {
      "id": "dd96f2b409481bc6b00e3e2a63f02e3904f1e4fe",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 626,
        "name": "Quentin Bouget",
        "email": "quentin.bouget@cea.fr",
        "username": "bougetq"
      },
      "date": "2017-05-23 08:25:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(3 comments)\n\nOverall, I think allowing users to set and (more importantly) to get information about a private structure is not the best thing. It constrains the implementation of the changelog api. If the api were to stop using a buffer, I don't think there would be an easy/non-breaking way to reimplement this function.\n\nI think giving hints to the llapi would be a less intrusive method. It would allow applications to say: \"I can process more changelogs if you can give me more\", or \"I am a slow application anyway, no need to go above and beyond for me\". Applications would not have strict expectations, and the operations could easily be no-ops if they do not make sense in the future.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
